Oct 4 2009 	Great stay at the Plaza	I traveled to Vegas with a buddy of mine and stayed here for nine nights. My room was on the 21st floor of the south tower and had a great view of the Stratosphere Tower, a few of the other hotels on the strip, and, of course, the mountains to the south and west. If you keep in mind that this place is 38 years old, it has withstood the test of time and thousands of guests well. The room was a little bit dated but more than adequate. It would be similar to a room you might expect at a Days Inn or Super 8. The only thing I thought was in rough shape was the carpet which had more than a few cigarette burns, and obviously isn't vacuumed very often. Quite honestly, the only time I saw a vacuum while I was here was in the lobby and on the main floor of the casino. The pool was a little small for the size of the hotel, but was clean and well maintained and never too crowded. There is even a poolside bar open Thursday thru Sunday, something I didn't expect for the price of the hotel. The casino was about average size and has an excellent variety of slots and table games with low minimums. All bartenders were friendly and accomadating, and always comp your drinks if you play video poker. All hotel employees for that matter seem very friendly and helpful. The location directly across from the Fremont St. experience is outstanding, and you can access the Strip or the airport from this location quickly and cheaply on the bus. There were about 50 or 60 TV channels in the room, but who goes to Vegas to watch TV?! The only downside to this hotel is the buffet , which looks cheap and thrown together. The &quot;steak&quot; was thinly cut pieces of roast beef! The food reminded me of my days in military chow lines or in the high school cafeteria. Would recommend the buffet at Main Street Station down the street, which offers much better food at about the same price. All in all, had a good experience and would gladly stay here again. I'm a 28 year old single male and the hotel seems popular with a lot of people my age, as well as older retired people, frequent Vegas visitors, and, like any other downtown hotel, Filipino and Hawaiian people.	
