Jul 12 2009 	Good spot on the cheap in classic Vegas	Stayed at the Plaza from June 7-11 and again June 18-20. When my husband and I travel, our basic needs are clean and safe. Our standards of clean may vary from other folks, so read on...((And keep in mind, our standards were even lower in Vegas, since literally the room was place to shower and sleep only.))The first room was in the South Tower, we upgraded to a Strip view, which was not as spectacular as it sounds, but it included a view of the Greyhound station below, haha! The room was clean, but musty due to age. The bathroom was clean, but again, a little dated...the caulk around the tub edge was peeling and there were a few areas where it looked like there had been a water leak. However, the shower water was hot and forceful and never ran out, perfect for washing the Vegas out of your hair. The air conditioner froze over the last night we were there, but since we were leaving anyway, did not bother with maintenance. The second room was in the North Tower, which has been remodeled. First thing, I checked the bed for bed bugs, and while I did not find any, there was a gross brown stain on the sheet, so we asked switch rooms immediately. There was no hassle, the staff was very apologetic. The room still had a bit of a mustiness to it, but had a newer feel to it. The shower situation was about the same as the first time. The iron had a black burnt spot on it, which I did not notice at first, nearly ruined a new shirt. Both times, the beds were comfortable, but could have used more pillows. The Plaza has a late check-out policy, for an extra $20, you can stay in your room til 6pm, which was great for us since we were leaving on a midnight flight. Allowed us to sleep most of the day and re-coup for the night.Would I recommend this hotel to a friend? If you can handle some age and mustiness, the Plaza is no problem. If you prefer a more modern feel, you might consider another place.The hotel and casino staff were all very helpful and friendly. The hotel has a 24 hour McDonald's in addition to a pizza shop and a buffet restaurant, but we did not eat there. My husband had stayed at the Plaza before, so most of our stay was comped, however, rooms in the area are very cheap all around. Our goal was to gamble, play poker, stay up all night and just go non-stop, so Fremont St. was perfect for us. We didn't spend much time gambling in The Plaza. It's walking distance to Binion's, spent a lot of time in the poker room there. The Golden Nugget is nearby, the pool and spa are fantastic. Fremont St. is having a summer promotion called the &quot;Summer of 69&quot; so most of the dealers and staff were wearing tie-dyed shirts, there was a live show every night on the street, with music from that era. And the Fremont St. experience included music from Kiss and Queen. We are in our 30s and the crowd tended to be older than us. You are fine on Fremont, but be careful venturing too far away, especially at night, the neighborhood gets dodgy quickly. However, I never felt unsafe walking around by myself on Fremont at 3am.The vibe in old Vegas is much different than downtown. If you want dancing fountains and night clubs, this area might not be for you. If you want to gamble, stay on the cheap, meet all sorts of Vegas characters and have a bit more mellow experience overall, head to Fremont and The Plaza.As a friend of ours who lives in Vegas put it, &quot;I would worry about most people in that part of town, but you guys are adventurous and can handle it.&quot; :-)	
