Feb 17 2009 	Not bad but not particularly good either.	Thankfully it was cheap.This was my first visit to Vegas. I wasn't looking for anything lavish, but I expected a little more from a Downtown Vegas hotel.The room was bigger than I had expected and it was clean, so that was good. The beds were made nicely, the floors were clean and the bathroom and all its fixtures were clean and there were plenty of towels.The beds were not all that comfortable. The very small TV was probably 15 years old and the picture was green. When the cold water was turned on to a certain pressure, the pipes in the walls made a very annoying sound.The elevators were a serious fault to me. The North Tower that I stayed in has 6 elevators, but 2 of them are reserved for hotel services, leaving 4 small, slow elevators for all the guests of the tower. Each time I needed an elevator, there was a painfully long wait and the small elevators were nearly always packed full of 10-12 people at a time. There was a bit where I had to go downstairs a few times within an hour or so. Each time I got an elevator, it was the same one, making me think it was the only one running, on a busy Saturday night no less. I heard complaints from probably 10 other guests on the elevators about how ridiculously slow they were. If you're going somewhere and have a certain time to be there and you have to pass through a Plaza elevator, be sure to give yourself an extra 20 minutes just in case.The Plaza's Lucky 7 Buffet ($7.77) was horrible as well. I only found 2 items that were edible. The rest of the slop they were serving I wouldn't feed to a stray dog. Main Street Station just 1 block north of the Plaza has an excellent buffet for only $7.99.For the price, it wasn't all too bad, but for being a major spot in Vegas, I did expect more from it. Next time I go to Vegas I'll budget a little more for the room and stay at one of the nicer hotels on the Strip.	
Jan 13 2009 	Great Value	The Plaza Hotel is not a palace, or even close to it. If you're looking for a luxurious experience, go somewhere else. But if you just want a basic, clean room in downtown Las Vegas to sleep in, this place is for you.I've stayed here maybe 10 times in the last 15 years. I won't say I've never had a room with problems, but that's the exception rather then the rule. The rooms are medium size to large (but not suites). They are basic but clean and the beds are good. The bathrooms are small but everything works (usually). The 1 or 2 times I had a room with major issues like a running sink or a window that wouldn't close, I was moved to a better room (there are over 1000 rooms here).There are 2 towers. The South Tower is the cheaper one, I just had a room there for $35/night. You can pay a little more and stay in the North Tower. I've stayed in both and there's not much difference.The buffet is $7.77 and runs all day. It's not the best one in Vegas but it's worth $7.77 and you get filled up. In the bars, beers are $2 and so are many mixed drinks. There is a sports bar overlooking Fremont Street with rock bottom drink prices. I think the casino's pretty good too. I've come away a winner more than once.I didn't turn on the small TV because I don't go to Vegas to watch TV, I go to gamble and party.If you're a picky person or someone who wants to make an impression on your group, stay somewhere else. If you want a clean basic room for a great low price, go to the Plaza. I love it.	
