Sep 7 2008 	Good value for the unfussy traveller	We managed to get a &quot;petite suite&quot; for $59 for a Friday night stay, and we were more than pleased with the value it represented. Sure, the decor is not spanking new and there is a slight mustiness to the place but trust me it is not half as bad as some of the hotels we went into in Vegas which postively reeked. The room we had (10th floor in the North Tower) had a fantastic view of Fremont St, we could watch the ceiling show from our balcony, and the air conditioning was a little noisy but not something that would stop you sleeping (and you probably need a little noise to drown out the Freemont experience noise which is pretty full on and goes on late into the night!). We loved the swimming pool on the 7th floor, great music playing, loads of sunbeds and a bar. Check in was fairly quick and reasonably personable. Only negatives were the cleaning standards (ie our balcony had been left with cigarette butts on it and the bathroom tiles were not completely mildew free!) and the fact that our balcony door had a faulty lock, which they kept saying they would fix and rather charmingly told us we would not be insured if we left our belongings in the room and they were stolen, but sure this was a one off problem and wouldn't affect most of the rooms. We had already stayed on the strip at the beginning of the trip so didn't miss it but I would say the Fremont St area is quite different to the rest of the strip and only worth staying in once you have experienced what the strip has to offer as it's a relatively small contained area and obviously has a lot less choices of places to eat/drink/gamble/just plain sightsee. But if you want to stay in the Fremont St area it is a good value short stay if you are not too bothered about pristineness and plan to spend most of your time out and about rather than in the room!	
