Nov 1 2007 	Shabby relic of old Vegas.	This was my first experience of staying at a hotel in downtown and may well be my last. Sadly, the only thing that the Plaza has going for it is its location.This was a short stay option during a much longer trip. We booked in for a weekend - when prices on the strip go through the roof. Given the price and the age of the property I wasn't expecting much but the Plaza disappoints on all levels. Rooms are dreadfully dated and shabby as are the corridors and other common areas. Rooms not facing Freemont have a wonderful view of the railway goods yard. You can hear every one of the seemingly endless freight trains that rumble past day and night. Service is pretty patchy, as are cleaning standards and overall the hotel has a terminally grubby feel. On a good trip to Vegas you can expect to spend very little time in your hotel room but you really shouldn't dread going back to it. I love old Vegas and I'm sure that the Plaza was a great destination in its day but now it's just depressing. Total rennovation or swift implosion is the only thing for it.	
Oct 30 2007	Clean room Good Service for $42 a night can't be beat!	Clean Room, Good ServiceMy wife and I stayed just one night on October 24th, 2007, and while a lot of people complain about the old Plaza, I say what do you expect, the Ritz Carlton? We paid $47 (including taxes) for a room with a charming view of the air conditioning coolers and the south tower. The following are the goods and the not so goods:Goods:1. The room was large, much larger than a hotel recently built.2. The staff was super friendly.3. The location cannot be beat.4. The show Viva Las Vegas at 2 and 4 on weekdays only cost us $2.75 a head to see it.. It was pretty good. A cheesy emcee, scantily clad dancing girls, a magician that makes stuff appear and disappear, and a comedian that insulted the crowd. 5. The buffet at the nearby Main Street Station is excellent. I have eaten at the Flamingo, Stratosphere, Bally's, Excalibur, the Sahara, and unfortunately Circus Circus and despite being about twice the price of the Main Street Station, the Main Street was heads and shoulders above the rest. It was great.Not so Goods1. Our air conditioner in our room sounded like a garbage truck compacting garbage. I went to the front desk and they quickly changed our room to a room facing the Fremont Street Experience on the 16th floor.2. Our neighors, about 6 drunken frat boys were loud!!!. The walls seem to be toilet paper thin and we could almost partake in their conversations from our room.3. If your room faces The Fremont Street Experience, the noise is considerable. Also, Las Vegas' finest (fire and police) seem to make a lot of runs through the area with their siren's blaring. Overall, I would recommend it for an authentic Las Vegas Experience. It all seemed nice and clean. I have read about some things that people like to complain about, but hey, for $42 where else can you lay your head.	
Oct 23 2007	Plaza Breakfast Buffet and Viva Las Vegas show	We actually stayed at the Golden Nugget but we did visit the Plaza for the buffet breakfast on Sunday, as well as for the &quot;Viva Las Vegas&quot; show on Saturday.The show was quite inexpensive at about $11 a head. It is billed as some sort of &quot;vintage Vegas variety&quot; show. It consisted of essentially 3 acts: The Clever Emcee with a few acts, The Dancing Girls with the lead singer, and The Comedian.After the intro, the dancing girls start the show out with a bang, a big number with lots of costume and skin, along with the lead singer who does have a powerful voice, but unfortunately the audio system is a little on the tinny side and they run it up to just before distortion, so it's bordering on painfully loud. If the sound system had a little more low-end and mid-range, it would be much better, and if they'd not run the volume up so high, it'd be great.But the act is good, the singer belts it out well, and the dancers are entertaining and in good shape.The dancers and singer reappear several times during the show as well, and it seems like her singing gets a little louder each time. I finally resorted to small wads of tissue in the ears, as I was afraid of blood trickling out. Powerful voice. Lousy audio.The emcee is entertaining too. He's a funny guy, works the audience well, and later brings out a fairly amusing trained-dog act which has the audience laughing well. Nothing wrong with this guy really, well done and good timing.The final act, the Comedian, is pretty good. This guy is funny... he starts up a little slow but tips his hand with a few Rodney-esque moves with the tie, and then has us immediately in his grip with a crazed, almost Honeymooner-Gleason look, as he screams &quot;what the hell's WRONG with you people?!?&quot; He's on for probably 20 minutes and it's a fun time... we're laughing, sometimes hard.They wrap it up, we leave. All in all, a decent and entertaining show, and again, very reasonably priced. Despite the audio issues, we'd give it an 8.5.Not so for the buffet. Quite reasonably priced at $7.77, the food is average and the service spotty.We arrived at about 8:30 Sunday morning to find no line and maybe 2 or 3 customers eating. At the cashier/entry window, we asked if we might take a look at the food first, and they motioned us in. We scanned the trays, it was ok, so we went back to the little display case area behind the cashier's window and attempted to pay. The lady, whose back was facing us first (as she was looking out into the hotel area at her station), said somewhat bluntly, &quot;next time please go around and pay at the window&quot;. There were no customers waiting, the cashiers (2) were just standing there with nothing to do, and yet it appeared to me that they were quite flummoxed that I wanted to pay them, but I wasn't standing in the NORMAL place; I was 'inside'.After her comment, I said &quot;ok, do you want me to go back outside to pay you?&quot; and she relented, and said no, no, this is ok.Not a good start.Then our waitress was not having a good morning, I guess. She wasn't friendly at all, but rather acted as though she really would rather be somewhere else. We didn't feel like we bonded well at all. Might have been the intro at the cashier's table...She wasn't really rude, she was just really quiet, and when we asked for something later, we know she heard us but we didn't hear much of an acknowledgment... again, like she wasn't very happy to be there. I suppose waitresses have bad days and I know this isn't an easy job all the time but I'll have to admit, she was about the coldest fish I've ever dealt with in a restaurant.Whatever... the food was acceptable; although it could have been warmer, I think. The plates were stone cold going in, and the bins of food were rather lukewarm, apparently relying solely on the heat lamps above them for life.The eggs were available either scrambled or cooked as a sort of souffle with onion and peppers, and there was maybe one other combination I didn't try. There was a mountain of edible but not fabulous bacon, some sausage patties, potatoes, and a few other typical breakfast items... along with pork chops and essentially lunch as well. My wife tried a pork chop but she didn't finish it... it wasn't bad but it wasn't great either. They also had some pancakes and waffles under heat lamps, and some toast slices as well. There may have been other breakfast items but as I had filled my plate at that point, I wasn't aware of whatever else might have been available. I didn't notice any fruit, fresh or otherwise, other than some pineapple chunks and canned peach slices at the front of the line.I never did get asked for a coffee refill, and decided I didn't want to really ruin her day by asking for one, so we ate and left. It filled us up but all told, I'm guessing there are much better buffets available for breakfast, albeit probably at higher cost. Critics will be quick to point out that this is one of the least expensive buffets in town, which we are aware of, but it'd be nice to at least ask if we want more coffee.If a cheerful waitress was there, this experience would be quite different... so bear that in mind I guess... ymmv, as they say.You can get breakfast for a little less across the street at Golden Gate, and generally with enthusiastic and well-timed service, but the Plaza buffet is at least all you can eat, so it does have that going for it. We might try it one more time but we'd have to say 'recommended with caution' for now.	
