Apr 24 2007 	The beds were comfy	Booked a room at the Plaza because the rest of my travel group had booked there. I arrived to find that getting to check in required a trip up 3 floors and a walk through the hotel itself. Check in was speedy when I arrived but later on there was a long line and not enough staff to handle it quickly. Of note, the place stunk of cigarette smoke (poor ventilation). I got a non smoking room in the north tower (9th floor) that suprisingly didnt smell like smoke. My room had 2 chairs, a small table, 2 queen beds and a tv with remote. The bathroom had a small bottle of shampoo and a bar of soap. The TV had problems with the color and it got 10 channels.The casino was poorly lit and required the use of a respirator as there was a thick cloud of smoke throughout. Attached to the casino was the &quot;buffet&quot; and a lounge. I saw very few cocktail waitresses that were not assigned to the table games. Also on the 1st floor there is a McDonalds, Subway, diner, snack bar arcade and gift shop. There was a players club desk that gave away free t-shirts that advertised the hotels show &quot;Shag With a Twist&quot;The Plaza Buffet has a very small selection of food items and one would be better off going to the Golden Nugget or one of many other Fremont Street dining options.If one was to venture outside they would find wonderful Fremont Street directly across the street from the Plaza. There is a pool that was empty of water and 4 tennis courts on the 7th floor deck.All in all the Plaza was not a bad place to stay for a budget traveler since there were so many other options for gaming and diningon Fremont Street. If you are looking for a Strip quality hotel dont stay here but if you just need a place to sleep inbetween outings to other casinos, the Plaza gets the job done.	
Apr 24 2007 	Plaza is fine. Not spectacular but fine.	I needed a room for just one night, a Saturday. There was something major in town that weekend--a horse show I think--and everywhere I checked either (a) was sold (b) wanted a two night minimum, or (c) wanted at least $400 for that one night. I like the California and Main Street Station downtown but they were sold. The Plaza was willing to give me a Saturday night room for a mere $159, which I thought was too much for the Plaza, but it was way better than anywhere else, so I took it. I really do like downtown as I can walk to things, including a Walgreens. I've recently had bilateral knee surgery and a broken foot, so not having to walk for miles just to get thru a hotel is a major draw to me.I was surprised to find that check-in is on the third floor. I'd never been to the Plaza before but I suspect they gave up their lobby space to the fast food restaurants (subway, mcdonalds, etc.) so they could actually get some income from that street level space. There was no line to check in and the clerk was friendly.My room was one of the &quot;deluxe&quot; rooms, in other words, I went one level up from the base when I booked the room. It was supposed to be a non-smoking room, but it wasn't. However, the only reason I know this is because there were ashtrays with matchbooks on the nightstand and in the bathroom. I didn't smell anything and I normally am real sensitive to the smell of smoke.The room was....shabby. It was shabbier than the Sahara. BUT, it was clean. I have no complaints. Sure it would have been nice to have nicer furniture and newer carpet, and so forth, but there was nothing wrong with the room. It was just...not new. And that, no doubt, is why it wasn't $400.The bathroom, though oddly laid out (probably a remodel at some point to put in a better sink, toilet, and tub), was large, clean, and worked just fine. There was no coffeemaker (but I don't drink coffee), and there was no hair dryer which I did really need. It was also very quiet. My room over looked the railroad tracks and though I saw a train go by, I didn't hear a thing.I'm not a gambler so I can't speak to the casino. I walked thru part of it just to see what it was like and it pretty much looked like every other casino.I would stay at the Plaza again, but preferably when the rates are more like they usually are here. However, in a pinch, when everything else is sold or outrageous, it was perfectly acceptable.	
