Jul 8 2006	Great place will return to the Plaza again and again!	I've been coming to Vegas for 14 years. For the first 13 years, I always stayed on the strip. The Vegas strip has become too tiring, too crowded, and too expensive. It's become a joke, really. Bad odds, expensive food, and everything is a cattle call. There are no more deals to be had there, and between people pushing strollers and the card flippers, it's become a pain to walk more than a couple of blocks.While I'd visited downtown many times, I had never stayed there. For my trip in May, I decided to change that. Being a movie fan, I decided to stay at The Plaza. You see, The Plaza has been featured in many films, including Casino, The Stand, and Back To The Future II. My curiosity got the best of me, and I made my reservation. The Plaza is currently undergoing a remodel and restoration. Most people who stay there don't realize this, mainly because the staff and the workers are doing it one piece at a time, and in such a way that it will have the smallest impact on guests. Ask anyone working there though, and they'll tell you all about it. The best thing is, there are no plans to raise room rates once the renovations are complete! The Plaza will just keep getting better and better. Check-in was a bit odd, the main 'lobby' area of the hotel has been converted into the Players Club signup. Registration is on the newly remodeled 3rd floor. A bit odd to find it at first, but once I got there, I was impressed. Lots of friendly staff behind the counters, and they were always smiling. They seemed very interested in any questions I had, and accomodated my room requests without making any big deal out of it. The new lobby itself is a knockout, very classy and elegant. Very spacious too, I can see why they moved it. It has a new lounge there, which adds to the ambience. If this is what they're planning on doing with the rest of the hotel, I'm intrigued already. I had a smoking room on the 7th floor. It was very large, and included an easy chair with ottoman. Very comfortable. The room was clean, but the furniture was older and the carpet was worn with age. No big deal. The bathroom was clean. I've actually seen worse on the strip and paid twice as much for it! On that trip, I only stayed one night and didn't explore much else in The Plaza. A month later (June) I came back to Vegas with friends for a few days, and after my experience the month before, we decided to skip the strip altogether, and we got rooms at The Plaza again. Again, I got a great welcome from the helpful staff at check-in. This time, I got a smoking room on the 19th floor, while my friends got a non-smoking room on the 17th floor directly below mine. These were both North tower rooms. Both rooms faced Fremont, and had a great view. There was no noise from the FSE or anything else going on down there. Very quiet, overall. Again, the room I had was in similar shape to the room in May. Clean, comfortable, but worn. However, my friends in the non-smoking room had all new carpeting, new furniture, a fridge in the armoire... the room was fantastic! And, here in lies one of the biggest secrets about Vegas hotel rooms: Smoking rooms are the last ones to get renovated, always. If you're a smoker, and the hotel offers rooms with a balcony, get a non-smoking room, and smoke outside. You'll always have a much nicer room.On this trip, I was able to check out the hotel and casino much more. I ate breakfast and dinner at the buffet, and it was OK for breakfast. Nothing special, and it was inexpensive. Dinner was also cheap, but not that good. It's small, and has a very limited selection. There are a few other places downtown that charge $5 more (about $10-12 total) with much better food, and much wider selection. The coffee shop closed down for renovation on my second day, so I didn't get a chance to check it out. No big deal, Binions, The Cal, and The Vegas Club all have excellent coffee shops that are open 24 hours, are literally a 3 minute walk away, and are also very inexpensive with quality food. The Keno lounge was small, but it looked like they were looking to expand that area, too. The chairs were comfortable, and the staff was great. Drinks came often. I don't play Bingo, but their Bingo room was huge, and from some of the people I talked to, this was the place to go to for Bingo in Vegas. I'll take their word for it.The table games area of the casino was large and wide open, unlike a lot of places where you can barely walk through it. The sports book was large, had stadium seating for watching games, and had lots of seats with personal TVs for racing bettors. I'll be spending more time there on the next trip!The slot area takes up the largest part of the casino floor, which is bigger than it looks. The Plaza does a great job with organizing the slots - there's plenty of room around them, yet they have a huge amount and variety of games available. You can barely walk through some of the slot areas in other casinos, not true here. After my two stays at The Plaza, I started reading reviews on this website, which is what prompted me to write this review. I have to seriously ask, what are some of these reviewers expecting? For $29 a night, you're getting a room and amenities that surpass all but the top luxury hotels in most cities! Some people have complained that the Greyhound bus terminal is 'right there' and brings in a lot of riff-raff. The bus terminal is on the 16 acre property, but it is not 'right there.' It's far from the entrance of The Plaza. This is downtown Las Vegas, the riff-raff is already built in, they don't need a bus terminal! For what it's worth, I've seen more panhandlers and actual homeless people on the strip. Also, downtown doesn't have the card-flippers passing out ads for women on every single corner! There's also much less litter, and much more breathing room on the FSE than you'll ever find on the strip. Because of the cheaper prices and better odds, downtown does attract some lower income people. From reading reviews, I think this is what really irks some people the most. I think maybe they see someone in blue collar working clothes and assume they're homeless. In reality, everyone I've met and talked to downtown is friendly an articulate. There are also a lot of visitors from Asia, UK, and Canada that stay there for the bargains. Vegas has something for everyone, and if paying $300 a night so you can rest comfortably knowing that there's faux marble columns in the lobby of your hotel is your thing, then don't come to The Plaza. If you come downtown at all, stay at the Golden Nugget. However, if you don't care what your lobby is made of, want a great room at a great hotel at a great price, stay at The Plaza.	
Jul 5 2006	Do yourself a favor stay elsewhere!	Upon arrival by car we had a terrible time trying to park. The parking garage attendant told us we had to pay $10.00 to park our car or go down the street to the other parking lot. Upon arrival at teh other parking lot we were promptly turned away, this attendant told us this parking lot was for special event guests only and since we were checking into hotel we needed to go to the other parking lot we just came from. Well, we explained to the gentleman what the other parking lot attendant told us. He went ahead and called the other parking lot attendant and the told us to go down there again. So off we go. This time the lot attendant being well informed asked us for drivers license for id and room reservation confirirmation then went and checked some list before giving us the go ahead to enter the parking ramp. this all took about half an hour!  Finally we arrived on the 3rd floor of the parking ramp parked the car and went into the building to check in. Check in process was smooth and the clerk was courteous.Our room was on the 18th floor. We requested a non smoking king bed which we got.The room was very large but had an odor of mold and old cigarettes. the carpet was badly soiled and stained. the bathtub had virtually no caulk around it and was pretty gross looking at best. the wallpaper in the bathroom was peeling and the bath room was extremely small. The couch and love seat was badly stained also. Thank goodness the sheets were clean anyway. Pillows you call those little tiny things a pillow? bed as very firm borderline comfy. Ceiling was philthy from the a/c blowing dirt from the filters.Casino .. hmm very dirty and smokey. Put $60.00 in a penny machine and went to my room an hour later. Machines just were not paying and not just for me either! Early morning riser I looked for a cup of coffee at 6 am but ended up going down Fremont street to grab coffee at the doughnut shop down there.The price was cheap maybe to cheap. I think I will spend the few extra dollars and stay on the strip at a better hotel from now on. I have stayed in Vegas many times and tried many different hotels and this is the first one that I will never go back too!	
