Sep 13 2005	Really Wanted to Love the Plaza But...	This report is long over-due. Hopefully I'll post pics in future. We arrived at The Plaza Hotel at around 1:30 PM. Check in was not until 3:00 PM but the clerk stated that early check-in would not be a problem. I asked him if there were any low-cost or no-cost upgrades available. The clerk said that he would check and after a couple minutes of keyboarding he announced that he'd given us &quot;a bit of an upgrade&quot;.We got the 15th floor, room 1502, very close to the elevators and a nice view of Fremont Street.As far as the room itself went, it was fine. It was old and a bit shabby but clean. The carpet didn't make you afraid to walk around barefoot, but definitely needed to be replaced. I did lay towels in the dressing area/sink area as the carpet was very discolored. The room was a little larger than a standard (or so I'm guessing) as it had a small sitting area that looked out the sliding door down at Fremont Street and the canopy. The king sized be was comfortable enough and we had a fridge. The bathroom consisted of a toilet and shower and a separate area for the sink. In this area there was also a fridge &amp; a place to hang your clothes. The balcony was in desperate need of a washing down, however.Normally I don't find a small bath to be that much of a problem but, the shower in this case way TOO undersized. You could not take a shower without the shower curtain sticking to you. In addition the drain was extremely slow. I called maintenance to get it looked at. They were at our room within 20 minutes. After working on the drain for ten minutes or so the worker declared that the drain was fixed. Housekeeping was unavailable so the maintenance guy brought us some fresh towels to replace the ones he'd mopped up with.The drain was moderately improved but not by much. I did want to love the Plaza with it's history and location. Alas I can only give it a moderate recommendation. It's not horrible, but there are better places to stay for the price.	
Aug 14 2005 	Great Location Need Some Work!	I have stayed several times at the Plaza over the last two years. Each time, the food has been much better than expected; especially the Sunday Brunch in the Showroom that was started by Larry Manetti. The diner isn't bad and their bottled water is a bargain in the convenience store (compared to the major Strip hotels).Bathrooms are kind of cramped, but the water pressure was okay and warm enough. The decor of the rooms could definitely be improved. To echo another trip commentator, &quot;spend a few bucks and I'll spend a few more each night to stay at your hotel.&quot;The location can't be beat. Personally, there are enough ways to lose your money without going down on the Strip. The shows,- if you search through the various acts playing at any one time, are quite appealing. The Fremont Street Experience has pumped life back into the downtown area. The street kiosks, entertainers and stage acts add some more pizzazz to a stay in this area.The Plaza showroom and Comedy club have some decent attractions. They need to upgrade their entertainment in what they call the Lounge area which is a stage that exists at the end of the bar off the casino floor. More rotational acts and some that are actually known by the younger set might lure a new breed of clientele into the Plaza. The casino staff, for the most part, is friendly, but you still get those occasional dealers or croupiers that have an &quot;attitude&quot;. I work hard to save my money so I can come to Vegas to gamble and entertain myself. I'd like to feel that those that are taking my money feel somewhat happy about their life's work.Their sports book needs a renovation. I enjoy traditional items but if you're going to place a bet at a Vegas book, you begin to measure them by the feel and ambiance set forth by those at the Venetian, Wynn, etc. I would compromise and install a setup similar to Harrah's which would greatly elevate the status of this area of the hotel. Vegas has gone back to being upscale and the only way a venue can compete is to be one notch better than they have in the past.The front desk staff seems disorganized. They need to have a better system for check-in, especially when there is a large contingent checking in, all at the same time. I felt like the front doors were going to whack me in the butt. When we checked in, there was only one bellman on duty. Is Vegas not operating 24 hours a day anymore?Overall, the location is excellent, the rooms so-so, the food isn't bad for the money and the Sunday Brunch is one of the town's best values. Vegas needs a quality mid-range hotel and if the management could ever get their act together on all counts, their ranking could easily be in the top 50 hotels in the Vegas area.One final note. I'm a non-smoker, which puts me in a minority inside any casino. A N/S area for slots and some tables games would be great. I played bingo one time and would have enjoyed playing a few more sessions, but the smokers kept me and some other patrons from being able to enjoy yourself. Bingo is part of your daily take, right?This was written by a blue collar guy who appreciates value, service and friendliness.	
Aug 9 2005	Good Place to Just Crash and Go	This is a typical economy hotel. We took the place because we got a terrific price, my husband loves downtown, and we were looking for a place to sleep and keep our stuff. It's at the end of Fremont street, so you just walk out and you're right in the mix. For me, I could take an $8 cab ride to the Sahara and pick up the monorail and hang out on the strip all day. Do not take the bus - the trip from the strip to downtown took 20 minutes for the bus to come and then a hot, crowded hour back (that was on two occasions, one evening and one afternoon). Once I figured out to buy an unlimited ride week pass ($20) on the monorail and just shelled out the $20 a day in cab fair and tips, I was much happier.My comments are basically on the room, since I just used the place to sleep. We were in room 828 in the North Tower. The room was good size with two double beds (no king's left, but that didn't bother us). There is a funny little smell that I only noticed for about the first 10 minutes of the trip. The bathroom has the toilet and shower in one tight little room, and the sink and place to hang clothes outside. I like this so I can be gussying up while my husband's in the shower. Two large adjacent mirrors in the bathroom and a very large mirror that covers the wall outside the sink area - so if you need to see yourself, no problem. The water pressure, temperature, and drain was fine while we were there.The beds were typical and comfortable enough. Maid service came by early (around 8:00 am - who's up by that time in Vegas?) and I was worried they would come in since there is no chain lock. It seems the little lock on the door works the same way (I found this out when I locked my husband out while I was in the shower). Be sure to put your do not distrub sign out before you go to bed. Our area was really quiet.The decor was a little 80's and the view was tops of parts of the building and a vacant lot. Everything was very clean and kept up nice. Housekeeping brought me an iron about 20 minutes after I called, that seemed quick enough for me. THEY DO NOT PROVIDE HAIRDRYERS! That's a note for those of us big haired gals. The air conditioner worked very well, but it was a bit noisy. There was a small TV with just a few channels and refrigerator in the room. Overall, I'd stay again if the price was nice and low.	
