Aug 26 2004	Alot of FUN!	Ok.. I read the reviews for the hotels I stay at and usually agree. But, the reviews for this hotel are ridiculous to me. I stayed at the Plaza for 7 nights the first of May and never experienced any odor to in the rooms. In the casino, there was odor of smoke, but that is expected in smaller casinos. &lt;shrug&gt; We usually stay at the Stratosphere, but I wanted to try downtown and it was alot cheaper. Here was my experience...First, before I went, I read somewhere that if a person isn't satisified with their hotel room in Vegas, then it is their own fault for not complaining. We checked into the Plaza and had been upgraded from a Standard to Deluxe room at no charge. The Deluxe room had no hot water when we got there, but within 30 minutes, a repairman came in and fixed it. Looking out the window, I had no view (and for 7 nights, I really wanted one), so I went down to the front desk, killed them with kindness, and requested a better view. They told me they were sold out but to come down the next morning and they would change rooms. I went down about 9:00 and they gave me a new room number that would be available around noon. Come to find out, they upgraded again to a Petite Suite with a balcony overlooking Freemont Street. Just for ASKING!! This goes to show that they do TRY to help people who are dissatisfied. The rest of our trip was phenominal. Hubby made friends with the dealers on the poker tables and I made friends with the Pit Boss, Dealers, and even had a Casino Host visiting with me and gave me his card at Blackjack. Now, keep in mind that I never bet over $5 a hand a blackjack and hubby plays cheap Texas Holdum poker. So, none of this has to do with being a high roller, because we aren't. We go to Vegas on vacation one time a year and this was our first stay at the Plaza.Another hint is... if you sit at a table for awhile and make yourself noticed, you eat free at the Plaza. Can't say we paid for any meals there due to the comps and the coupons in the Plaza Pleasure Pak.I love this hotel. Unless attitudes change, it is where I choose to spend my time when in Vegas. Remember, killem with kindness!	
